comment_regular_data.body:
I'm very excited to finally see this feature included. Thanks @echasnovski for once again providing an excellent contribution.

However, I have one concern about this:

>This PR comments and uncomments blank lines while 'tpope/vim-commentary' does not.
It is a carefully thought through decision for a more intuitive experience at a cost of extra rules for how blank lines should be commented/uncommented.

I disagree that this is more intuitive, and in fact I would argue it's the opposite, in particular when un-commenting. Consider this example:

```c
// int x = foo();

// int y = bar(x);
```

The 2nd line is a blank line: there are no characters in it all. If I use the "toggle comment" operation on these 3 lines, what I get is the following:

```c
// // int x = foo();
//
// // int y = bar(x);
```

But what I would expect to see is

```c
int x = foo();

int y = bar(x);
```

This is rather annoying because when this happens I have to toggle the comments on the region again to get back to the original state, and then manually use the "toggle comment" operator on each individual line. For 2 lines that may not be a big deal, but for a less contrived, real world use case where there many such lines/individual regions, it becomes much more annoying.

I really feel strongly that this should not be the default behavior.

Here's a (untested) patch for the lockmarks binding:

```patch
diff --git a/runtime/lua/vim/_comment.lua b/runtime/lua/vim/_comment.lua
index e9cd662c9..ee045d9ae 100644
--- a/runtime/lua/vim/_comment.lua
+++ b/runtime/lua/vim/_comment.lua
@@ -197,14 +197,9 @@ local function toggle_lines(line_start, line_end, ref_position)
   -- - Debatable for highlighting in text area (like LSP semantic tokens).
   --   Mostly because it causes flicker as highlighting is preserved during
   --   comment toggling.
-  package.loaded['vim._comment']._lines = vim.tbl_map(f, lines)
-  local lua_cmd = string.format(
-    'vim.api.nvim_buf_set_lines(0, %d, %d, false, package.loaded["vim._comment"]._lines)',
-    line_start - 1,
-    line_end
-  )
-  vim.cmd.lua({ lua_cmd, mods = { lockmarks = true } })
-  package.loaded['vim._comment']._lines = nil
+  local saved_lockmarks = vim._lockmarks(true)
+  vim.api.nvim_buf_set_lines(0, line_start - 1, line_end, false, vim.tbl_map(f, lines))
+  vim._lockmarks(saved_lockmarks)
 end
 
 --- Operator which toggles user-supplied range of lines
diff --git a/runtime/lua/vim/_meta.lua b/runtime/lua/vim/_meta.lua
index 731dd5b92..430b7ea0a 100644
--- a/runtime/lua/vim/_meta.lua
+++ b/runtime/lua/vim/_meta.lua
@@ -34,3 +34,8 @@ vim.uri_from_fname = uri.uri_from_fname
 vim.uri_from_bufnr = uri.uri_from_bufnr
 vim.uri_to_fname = uri.uri_to_fname
 vim.uri_to_bufnr = uri.uri_to_bufnr
+
+--- @param value? boolean
+--- @return boolean : The previous value of lockmarks
+function vim._lockmarks(value)
+end
diff --git a/src/nvim/lua/stdlib.c b/src/nvim/lua/stdlib.c
index a5262efcf..4814f65cf 100644
--- a/src/nvim/lua/stdlib.c
+++ b/src/nvim/lua/stdlib.c
@@ -555,6 +555,22 @@ static int nlua_foldupdate(lua_State *lstate)
   return 0;
 }
 
+static int nlua_lockmarks(lua_State *lstate)
+{
+  const int save_lockmarks = cmdmod.cmod_flags & CMOD_LOCKMARKS;
+
+  if (lua_gettop(lstate) >= 1) {
+    if (lua_toboolean(lstate, 1)) {
+      cmdmod.cmod_flags |= CMOD_LOCKMARKS;
+    } else {
+      cmdmod.cmod_flags &= ~CMOD_LOCKMARKS;
+    }
+  }
+
+  lua_pushboolean(lstate, save_lockmarks != 0);
+  return 1;
+}
+
 // Access to internal functions. For use in runtime/
 static void nlua_state_add_internal(lua_State *const lstate)
 {
@@ -569,6 +585,10 @@ static void nlua_state_add_internal(lua_State *const lstate)
   // _updatefolds
   lua_pushcfunction(lstate, &nlua_foldupdate);
   lua_setfield(lstate, -2, "_foldupdate");
+
+  lua_pushcfunction(lstate, &nlua_lockmarks);
+  lua_setfield(lstate, -2, "_lockmarks");
 }
 
 void nlua_state_add_stdlib(lua_State *const lstate, bool is_thread)
```
